{{Infobox Korean name |context = north |hangul = 조선민주주의인민공화국 국적법 |hanja = 朝鮮民主主義人民共和國 國籍法 |rr = Joseon Minjujueui Inmin Gonghwaguk Gukjeokbeop |mr = Chosŏn Minjujuŭi Inmin Konghwaguk Kukjŏkbŏp }} The '''Nationality Law of the Democratic People's Republic of Korea''' (DPRK, commonly known as [[North Korea]]) governs who is a [[Citizenship in North Korea|citizen of the DPRK]], and how one may gain or lose such [[citizenship]].
==History== Until 1963, the DPRK had no formal nationality law. This led to situations which were quite unusual from the perspective of international law, most notably the [[Soviet Union]]'s unilateral declaration that the [[Sakhalin Koreans]] were DPRK citizens&mdash;in effect, one sovereign state granting its residents the citizenship of another sovereign state, presumably without any consultation.<ref name="Ginsburghs1983-19">{{harvnb|Ginsburgs|1983|p=319}}</ref>
The DPRK's first nationality law, passed on 9 October 1963, provided quite a broad definition of DPRK citizenship.<ref name="Ginsburghs1983-19"/> Specifically, it stated that anyone who had citizenship of undivided [[Korea]] and had retained it up to the promulgation of the new citizenship law, as well as descendants of such persons, was thenceforth a citizen of the DPRK.<ref>{{harvnb|Kim|1972|p=324}}</ref> This raised the possibility that every member of the [[Korean diaspora]] would be considered a DPRK citizen, as there had previously been no clear procedure for renunciation of Korean citizenship, and few had taken such an official step. The new law also established that foreigners could gain DPRK nationality by [[naturalization|naturalisation]].<ref name="Ginsburghs1983-19"/> The law was amended on 23 March 1995.<ref>{{citation|url=http://nk.joins.com/news/view.asp?aid=2691193&cont=law_genera|periodical=[[JoongAng Ilbo]]|title=조선민주주의인민공화국 국적법|date=2006-06-28|accessdate=2011-01-17}}</ref>
The law permits [[multiple citizenship]], and specifies that nationality treaties with other countries take precedence over the text of the law.<ref>{{harvnb|Kim|1972|pp=325&ndash;326}}</ref> Due to the lack of normal [[Japan–North Korea relations|diplomatic relations between the DPRK and Japan]], [[Koreans in Japan]] with dual citizenship of the DPRK and Japan have had their requests to renounce [[Japanese nationality law|Japanese citizenship]] in favour of solely retaining DPRK citizenship refused by Japan's [[Ministry of Justice (Japan)|Justice Ministry]].<ref>{{citation|periodical=[[Choson Sinbo]]|date=1999-03-25|accessdate=2011-01-17|url=http://www1.korea-np.co.jp/pk/087th_issue/99032507.htm|title=Korean-Japanese Here Seek Way to Make Tokyo Gov. Legally Recognize Their NK Citizenship|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120407131319/http://www1.korea-np.co.jp/pk/087th_issue/99032507.htm|archivedate=2012-04-07|df=}}</ref> It is also legally possible to renounce DPRK nationality; the DPRK issues certificates of loss of nationality in such cases, which may be required by other states in which a former DPRK national seeks to naturalise. However, such certificates have become more difficult to obtain {{asof|2011|lc=on}}, according to South Korean media reports.<ref>{{citation|url=http://english.chosun.com/site/data/html_dir/2011/01/07/2011010700252.html|periodical=Chosun Ilbo|date=2011-01-07|accessdate=2011-01-17|title=More N.Koreans Apply for Chinese Citizenship}}</ref>
