In [[real estate]] and [[real property law]], '''peaceable possession''' is "holding property without any adverse claim to possession or title by another". <ref>[http://dictionary.law.com/default2.asp?selected=1482&bold=%7C%7C%7C%7C Law.com dictionary]</ref>
[[Quiet title]] is used to refer to the new [[owner]]'s peaceable possession. [[Property title]], or [[ownership]], also includes [[Possession (law)|possession]], but is a greater [[property]] [[Rights|right]] than the latter. Therefore, peaceable possession may also refer to a [[leasehold estate|tenant]]'s, or [[lessee]]'s, warranty of [[Quiet enjoyment]], or require such for a quiet title action. <ref>[http://www.answers.com/topic/peaceable-possession?cat=biz-fin Answers.com web site]</ref>
[[Cotenant]]s take property together in peaceable possession.<ref> John Houston Merrill, et al., ''The American and English Encyclopedia of Law'' (1890), located at [https://books.google.com/books?id=K54BAAAAYAAJ&pg=RA1-PA1088&lpg=RA1-PA1088&dq=%22peaceable+possession%22&source=web&ots=OJ6K0Dn28L&sig=KgIh0u15eLkV_M_nhTRp0022Hxg]</ref> Peaceable possession is sometimes defined in the negative, that is, a [[trespass]]er ''lacks'' it. <ref>[http://www.canlii.org/ca/sta/c-46/sec42.html Canadian Legal Information Institute web site]</ref>
