The '''Plurinational Electoral Organ''' is the independent [[electoral branch]] of the government of Bolivia. It replaced the [[National Electoral Court of Bolivia|National Electoral Court]] in 2010. The branch consists of the 7-member Supreme Electoral Tribunal, the nine Departmental Electoral Tribunals, Electoral Judges, the anonymously selected Juries at Election Tables, and Electoral Notaries,<ref>{{Cite news | title = Posesionan a cuatro Vocales del Tribunal Supremo Electoral | work = La Jornada | accessdate = 2011-04-28 | date = 2010-08-16 | url = http://www.jornadanet.com/n.php?a=51574-1 }}</ref> as well as three operative branches. Its operations are mandated by the Constitution and regulated by the Electoral Regime Law (Law 026). The seat of the Organ and of the Supreme Electoral Tribunal are in La Paz; while the ruling [[MAS-IPSP]] party offered the headquarters to Sucre during the controversy over capital status during the [[Bolivian Constituent Assembly of 2006–2007|2006–07 Constituent Assembly]], negotiations were inconclusive. In June 2010, the Bolivian Senate rejected calls from [[Chuquisaca Department|Chuquisaca]] parliamentarians to place the headquarters in Sucre.<ref>{{Cite news | title = Senado: La Paz será sede del Órgano Electoral Plurinacional | work = La Razón | accessdate = 2011-05-08 | date = 2010-06-01 | url = http://www.la-razon.com/version.php?ArticleId=2776&EditionId=93 }}</ref>
The Organ's operative branches are the Civil Register Service ({{lang-es|Servicio de Registro Cívico}}, Sereci), the Intercultural Service for Strengthening Democracy ({{lang-es|Servicio Intercultural de Fortalecimiento Democrático}}, Sifde), and the Technical Unit for Oversight ({{lang-es|Unidad Técnica de Fiscalización}}, UTF). The Civil Register Service is charged with continually maintaining the electoral rolls and consolidates the functions of registering birth, marriage, death, biometric identification, and residence.<ref>{{Cite news | pages = E9 | title = Una apuesta decisiva: el Servicio de Registro Cívico | work = La Razón | date = 2010-04-24 }}</ref> The UTF audits and ensures the transparency of parties and political organizations.<ref>{{Cite news | pages = E10 | last = Bustillos Zamorano | first = Iván | title = La hora de la democracia intercultural | work = La Razón | accessdate = 2011-05-09 | date = 2011-04-24 | url = http://www.la-razon.com/version_temp.php?ArticleId=1494&EditionId=2517&idp=42&ids=279 }}</ref>
The first election to be supervised by the new Organ was the [[Bolivian judicial election, 2011|judicial elections of late 2011]], followed by special municipal elections.
==Supreme Electoral Tribunal== The '''Supreme Electoral Tribunal''' oversees elections nationwide. It consists of seven members, six of whom are chosen by the [[Plurinational Legislative Assembly]] and one designated by the President. There are also six alternate members chosen by the Assembly. The members of the Supreme Electoral Tribunal are<ref>{{Cite news| title = Posesionan a cuatro Vocales del Tribunal Supremo Electoral| work = La Jornada| accessdate = 2011-04-28| date = 2010-08-16| url = http://www.jornadanet.com/n.php?a=51574-1}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news| last = Mealla| first = Luis| title = El TSE consolida su Sala Plena después de 6 meses de espera| work = Página Siete| accessdate = 2011-04-28| date = 2011-01-14| url = http://www.paginasiete.bo/2011-01-15/Nacional/Destacados/4Nac001151.aspx}}</ref> as follows:
