The "'''presumption of legitimacy'''" is a [[common law]] rule of evidence that states that a child born within the subsistence of a marriage is deemed to be the child of the husband.
==Early history== [[Paternity (law)]] is considered an important issue in determining the [[Patrilineality#Agnatic succession|rules of succession]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://biotech.law.lsu.edu/Books/lbb/x650.htm|title=The Presumption of Legitimacy|accessdate=June 12, 2010}}</ref> [[Bastard (law of England and Wales)|Illegitimate children]] were originally excluded from royal succession, [[nobility|hereditary titles]], and property.
