The '''1810 Riksdag Act''' was passed by [[Riksdag|Parliament]] on 10 February 1810 during the [[reign]] of [[Charles XIII of Sweden|Charles XIII]]. It replaced the order of the estates meetings in 1617 reintroduced by [[Gustav III of Sweden|Gustav III]] via the [[Union and Security Act]] instead of the Riksdag Act 1723. The 1810 [[parliament]]ary regime was adopted after [[Sweden]] lost [[Finland]] and [[Gustav IV Adolf of Sweden|Gustav IV Adolf]] was pushed aside in a [[coup]]. Charles XIII was subsequently appointed [[regent]] and then [[king]], and after that a new form of government, the Government of 1809, was adopted. A notice of parliament which adopted the parliamentary order was issued in March 1809.

